caption.text:
‚ÄúHistoric.‚Äù‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
That‚Äôs the word Amanda Gorman (@amandascgorman) chose to describe this Inauguration Day in the United States.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
During today‚Äôs ceremony at the Capitol, Amanda, the very first US youth poet laureate, will recite a new poem titled ‚ÄúThe Hill We Climb.‚Äù‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
‚ÄúMy hope is to use language to speak to an America that is united and moving into the future with love and understanding,‚Äù says the 22-year-old.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
‚ÄúI am deeply indebted to the inaugural poets who‚Äôve come before me, and I am not missing out on the symbolism that I am the youngest inaugural poet ‚Äî and Black and female at that ‚Äî while the first female, woman of color vice president [Kamala Harris] is being sworn in.‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
This inauguration will be game-changing and add much-needed representation to the history books. It‚Äôs a privilege to be a part of it.‚Äù‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Photo of @amandascgorman by @kelianne

Japanese artist and designer Verdy (@verdy) always loved drawing characters. After years of doodling in notebooks, the iconic ‚ÄúVick‚Äù came to life. ‚úçüìí‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúI feel like we‚Äôve grown up together over many years,‚Äù says Verdy. ‚ÄúHaving the same personality as myself, he is always positive, takes on new challenges and is also pretty easygoing.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
The amount of time Verdy‚Äôs spent at home alone with his drawings last year gave him time to think about what‚Äôs important. ‚ÄúUp until now I thought I wanted to become an artist from Japan that gets to go out into the world. But now I want to be an artist that represents Asia.‚Äù üåè‚ú®‚Å£
‚Å£
If you‚Äôre needing some new year inspiration, #TakeABreak with Verdy (and his sidekick Vick) to see his work and passion in full force.

caption.text:
‚ÄúMy inspiration has been birthed from the richness of Black history ‚Äî the past, present and possibilities of the future,‚Äù says the artist Broadie (@bbrody04).‚Å£
‚Å£
His work clearly spans his connection to history. Some pieces reflect on African American spirituals like ‚ÄúWade in the Water‚Äù (pictured), while others depict modern pop culture figures or even iconic moments from the 1960s civil rights movement in the United States.‚Å£
‚Å£
On #MLKDay, Broadie looks back at Dr. King‚Äôs historic legacy, one that has informed his life and his work: ‚ÄúTo quote MLK, ‚ÄòI have decided to stick with love. Hate is too great a burden to bear.‚Äô I feel this quote shows how love continues to fight against hate, injustice and racism. Hate brings destruction and separation, while love connects people from all walks of life.‚Å£
‚Å£
Simply put, to me, MLK means Black excellence.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Art by @bbrody04

#HelloFrom the Tokyo Skytree.‚Å£
‚Å£

caption.text:
With bread-baker and writer Bryan Ford (@artisanbryan), it‚Äôs time to lose your expectations of bread and get experimental. üçû + üî• = üíØ‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúYour hands are powerful tools, eager to learn new things,‚Äù says Bryan, who fell in love with cooking as a child. ‚ÄúI remember helping my mom make tortillas, tamales and other traditional Honduran foods. As I got older, I started to work in restaurant kitchens and taught myself more about how to bake different types of bread and pastry.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
These days, Bryan infuses his Latin American heritage into fresh recipes and seeks new ideas from all over the world. ‚ÄúI love accounts that highlight different cultures and types of people that are cultivating their unique craft.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Check out today‚Äôs story for a glimpse into Brian‚Äôs kitchen and to learn a bit more about a few of his favorite Instagram accounts in the üåé of üçΩ.‚Å£
‚Å£
#ShareBlackStories üñ§‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo by @artisanbryan‚Å£

‚ÄúMy life is a product of Black history. Everything I do is to extend that legacy of building a better world than the one I received,‚Äù says writer and strategist Brea Baker (@freckledwhileblack).‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúWhen Trayvon Martin was assassinated in 2012, it sparked the beginnings of my activism. George Zimmerman‚Äôs acquittal over a year later is what would officially politicize me and send me deeper into this work. I became committed to understanding the deep-rooted legacy of racism in this country and how to break the cycle.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Brea was the youngest national organizer of the 2017 Women‚Äôs March and served as president of Yale‚Äôs NAACP chapter. Her involvement in multiple other civic engagement and advocacy efforts led her to take up her role in Inspire Justice, an organization which advises leading change-makers on social impact strategies.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúI have worked to create a world where profit and supremacy do not keep Black people, women and LGBTQ people from living safe and dignified lives. My work builds community and challenges the idea that we inherit a bunch of systems that can't be changed.‚Å£
‚Å£
I hope people leave rethinking everything, and especially the need for caging and policing human beings, and what‚Äôs possible if we come together.‚Å£
‚Å£
Young people are so powerful. We set the tone for the present and future of our global community. We are energetic and not so jaded by this world to lose faith in our ability to change it.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
#ThisWeekOnInstagram‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo of @freckledwhileblack by @syd.hol

preview_comments.text: @autumn.tx it‚Äôs literally a quote from @issarae the comedian that I‚Äôm referencing - relax y‚Äôall and just let a Black woman be great ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ú®

caption.text:
‚ÄúI‚Äôm passionate about exploring the relationship between social justice and environmentalism,‚Äù says activist and writer Leah Thomas (@greengirlleah), who founded IE (@intersectionalenvironmentalist), a community-building resource that inspires other activists to think about beyond climate change.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúMy work aims to challenge environmentalists to dive deeper and view environmentalism through a lens of intersectionality, so hopefully BIPOC don‚Äôt continue to be silenced in the issue, and so that environmental wisdom and conservation practices found in BIPOC communities can be celebrated and embraced as well. I‚Äôve found that most environmental activists that are spotlighted are white, even though BIPOC climate activists exist all over the world and have been doing this work for years.‚Å£
‚Å£
The Black community is disproportionately impacted by environmental injustice, COVID-19 and social injustice. This made me realize that the same systems of oppression are at play in each area. We must strive for racial justice so Black people can not only breathe and exist ‚Äî but thrive.‚Å£
‚Å£
It‚Äôs important that environmentalism is intersectional, so everyone has access to green spaces, nature and all that Mother Nature has to offer.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
#ThisWeekOnInstagram‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo of @greengirlleah by @cherthismoment

Educational influencer Blair Imani (@blairimani) uses unconventional, innovative methods to discuss complex issues. ‚ÄúI‚Äôve always been committed to advocacy, just the scale and focus had shifted throughout my lifetime. One of the great gifts of being an educator whose classroom is on Instagram is the ability to innovate at the drop of a hat, or hijab,‚Äù she says.‚Å£
‚Å£
Blair launched her series ‚ÄúSmarter in Seconds‚Äù on Reels, where she addresses topics like history, privilege, oppression and intersectionality theory through bite-sized lessons.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúThink of activism like a potluck ‚Äî your skills, networks and resources are your ingredients and recipes. Don‚Äôt try to bring something to the table that you don‚Äôt already have or can‚Äôt quickly learn how to make. Take stock of what others are bringing and see where your recipe fits in.‚Å£
‚Å£
2020 forced us to sit in the discomfort of racism and to look upon the world and take a mirror to ourselves and ask, ‚ÄòWho do we want to be? Who do I want to be?‚Äô‚Å£
‚Å£
We must decide what to do with this raised consciousness. Every one of us must ask ourselves, ‚ÄòWill I answer the call of history and materially change oppressive institutions? Or will I shut the door on the possibility of progress?‚Äô I‚Äôll be doing the former. I hope you‚Äôll join me.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
#ThisWeekOnInstagram‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo of @blairimani by @akeemomarali

Anna Maghradze‚Äôs (@anna_maghradze) digital collages border dreams and reality.‚Å£
‚Å£
Her ethereal, layered compositions offer transportation to magical worlds where pastel sunsets fill rooms and impossible scenarios are possible.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúThe hardest work is to come up with cool ideas,‚Äù says the graphic designer and photographer. ‚ÄúI try to find insights and moments that everyone has in their lives and show it in a different way. I like it more when the image is not entirely perfect and when it has a personal touch, so there is more room for mystery and more left to the imagination.‚Å£
‚Å£
The mood is surreal, escapist and minimalist. Two to three layers are enough to create something creative from photographs. I hope my audience feels calmness in my artworks.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
#ThisWeekOnInstagram‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo illustration by @anna_maghradze

Multidisciplinary artist Niko Christian (@cnikarts) uses his photography as a starting point to create new worlds. ‚ÄúA big part of my process, and how all this started, is based on my own mental chaos. I was looking for a way to create peace in myself, so I started trying to make work that embodies my own surreal euphoria.‚Å£
‚Å£
I draw inspiration from everywhere, but especially from my contemplations on the nature of existence and from nature itself. With an undercurrent of Utopian escapism, the dominant mood in my work is definitely surreal. Life is incredibly surreal when you think about it. All the things we take for granted, like trees, clouds, the ocean ‚Äî that any of it exists at all is wild.‚Å£
‚Å£
A recurring element in my work is the rainbow. This ties in thematically with a kind of polarity ‚Äî birth from death, or the dance of cosmos and chaos. One of the central ideas of these images is that things can transform and change really quickly when we lose sight of them, even for what feels like just a brief moment.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
#ThisWeekOnInstagram üåà‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo illustration by @cnikarts
